  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 4:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". As a contrast to this treatment of the apostles (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δέ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Luke notices the great increase of the church, which was effected by the address of the apostle. The number of believers had before this been above three thousand (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:47",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); by the present increase the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "number of men",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (the women, therefore, being not even included—on account of the already so considerable multitude of believers) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "came to be about five thousand",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The supposition of Olshausen, “that at first, perhaps, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "only",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " men had joined the church,” is arbitrary, and contrary to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 1:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". At variance with the text, and in opposition to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 5:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", de Wette makes women to be included.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
